Its old algae-stained coral surface chipped and malformed, this idol depicts a fish-like sea creature maneuvering through the water. Seashells, mother-of-pearl, and actual pearls laid into the petrified coral make it an obvious religious idol. Hawmin I, the earliest in the Wiltun dynasty, found this strange sea idol when they first settled this southernmost island in the Ruathym chain after arriving by sea from the northlands. They were then beset by "creatures from the sea" who claimed the rocky, salt-sprayed island as their own, and were summarily slain by Hawmin I and his settlers.
Idol taken in Conquest by Hawmin I

Value.value: Despite the erosion of the idol, it is clear from the dorsal fin and snout configuration that this fish is not a shark, as would signify an idol to Sekolah, but rather a dolphin. This is an ancient idol to Deep Sashelas, of the elven pantheon, known as the master of dolphins; could it be that the "creatures from the sea" were not sahaugin as many think, but rather aquatic elves defending an ancestral territory from foreign invaders?

Though the idol has been ill-maintained and many of its features eroded, it is most likely an idol of Sekolah, the demonic shark-god of the sahaugin - the only hostile "sea creature" amphibious enough to engage the settlers on land.
The creatures from the sea were obviously sahaugin, who probably climbed onto these rocks to perform evil rites; it was kill or be killed.

value.0:
Several banners hang here upon the wall, and unlike other exhibits, they do not appear to be antiquated at all. The father of the current ruler of Castle Wiltun, Lord Wiltun IV, had these banners hoisted high, not in honor but in triumph, before passing on and leaving Wiltun to the current ruler, his Grace Arsant Wiltun V. After ceding the Chief Axe of the Ruathym territories to a new ruler, the Wiltun dynasty returned to Castle Wiltun on the southern coast of Ruathym and there began a generation long campaign of shipbuilding and naval training that has earned Wiltun its position as the strongest naval power in Ruathym, and a serious maritime contender along the Trackless Trader's Route. Over fifteen years ago, a single act of piracy against a Luskanese trade vessel resulted in a long-standing naval war between Ruathym and Luskan. The pirate ship flew the colors of Ruathym, though the Chief Axe and all subordinate jarldoms deny the aggressive act. Following this encounter, the Chief Axe of Ruathym supplied vast resources to Wiltun IV and the jarldoms fleet. This naval war ended only by the forceful ceasefire imposed by the Lord's Alliance, a league of nations along the Sword Coast, only to be replaced by a faulty land war as Luskan attempted to invade Ruathym. With the aid of the Lord's Alliance yet again, in paritcular Lord Liriel Baenre of the Alliance, the Luskanese were rebuffed. Tensions remain high, and volleys are to this day fired between the ships of these two nations when they should happen to cross in open waters. 

Click to investigate.
Naval War Trophies of Lord Wiltun IV

Value.value: The modern history book will tell you a random pirate attack started this war, but from what you know of seamen's tales, it was a secret Umberlant fleet, the Kraken Society, who flew the Ruathym flag to start this conflict against those who would sail the Bitch Queen's seas without her favor. The Kraken Society reaches far and wide, and you've heard a Waterdhavian captain is under suspicion. The Kraken Society ranges from all ports around the Trackless Sea and beyond, so their members could be from anywhere, even Ruathym. A fitting sacrifice to Umberlee is the flotsam and jetsam of sunken ships and the blood of men. And after just such an occurrence over fifteen years ago, Castle Wiltun came into remarkable resources from the capitol to aid it in preparing for war...

Ruathym denies the claims that they initiated this naval war with an act of piracy, and they are right to do so; according to gossip you've heard from seamen on your travels, there is a subversive, Umberlant group called the Kraken Society who seeks to honor the Bitch Queen by bringing strife to men who would sail her waters without her favor. Thanks to their meddling, Lord Wiltun V may have an opportunity to leave his own legacy of war, conquest, and triumph behind, as well.

Arsant's father left a real legacy behind, as did all of those before him. These are big banners that belonged to big Luskan ships, and it must have taken a strong navy to sink them. If there's anything you know, its that Lord Wiltun V has some mighty big shoes to fill.

A post of very old wood with equally ancient and malformed skulls thrust upon it like pearls on a string necklace. Hawmin I struggled to defend his settlement against the many monstrous tribes of Ruathym, and his son, Hawmin II, became proactive in slaying a race of giant trolls who lived in submerged caverns along the shoreline. This is his tribute to the greatness of the Wiltun dynasty.
Troll Skull Collection of Hawmin II

Value.value: Due to the impact of starvation from lack of agriculture on this island chain, these settlers could not have fought these giant trolls alone. Clearly, they had help; you recall the Historie of Island Nomads, penned by Rogerio over 100 years ago, stating that a large tribe of humans may have come to the Ruathym chain from the Moonshaes some generation or two before the northlanders arrived in Ruathym. They were a peaceful tribe, and skilled warriors; there must have been an accord between this tribe and the early Wiltun settlers.

Considering the number of skulls upon this post and their relative size compared to the human skull, it is a true marvel that the original barbaric settlers were able to take them on alone - this island afforded no agriculture for the original settlers to provide food. Starvation alone, according to the historic trend of foreigners settling in harsh territories, should have wiped out Hawmin I's northlanders and made them easy pickings for these trolls.
If it weren't for Hawmin II, you'd probably be getting eaten by these nasty trolls. Three cheers for Hawmin II!

value.0:
Click to investigate.

A crude, cast-iron sword with a heavy center and sharp edges, a blade that could only have been wielded by a true brute: Bargugh the Black was an Orkish King who inhabitated and in fact dominated the monstrous tribes of Ruathym's central island. Hawmin III, to avenge his father Hawmin II, who was slain by Bargugh himself, gathered his people and invaded the Orkish tribal lands, driving them out with the sheer tenacity of northlander fury. This sword remains as a tribute to the blood that has been shed to secure not only the Wiltun jarldom, but the whole of the Ruathym island chain.
Sword of Bargugh the Black, Slain by Hawmin III

Value.value: This harsh island where Castle Wiltun is build could not have sustained more than a hundred people when it was originally settled, and clearly more than half of them should have starved. This lends credence to the assertion that they had help from a second tribe of warriors who came from the Moonshaes, as described by Rogerio in his Historie of Island Nomads, and together they effectively cleaned the Ruathym island chain of its monstrous inhabitants, and there began the even greater settlement of Ruathym, now this island chain's capital city and the centralmost of all four jarldoms.

It is even less believeable that Hawmin III's generation should be able to strike down an entire orkish hoard alone as his father's generation was able to slay a hundred monstrous trolls. If this truly happened as it says, they either had help, or some old skald really exaggerated the story. Which is not unsurprising, considering that the territory the orkish tribe held is supposedly now where the capital city of the Ruathym chain now stands: Ruathym itself.
Only an ork could have or would have wielded a blade like that. It must have been a truly epic battle! Where is a bard to tell it all in gruesome detail when you need one?

A hideous taxidermized war trophy; though the face has vaguely human features, the mouth is open and snarling, the eyes black as pitch, and the skin an eerie mudbrick red. The head itself is large, with a dense skull and a thick browline, seeming primitive and dangerous. Its slaying is credited to Hawmin IV, predecessor to Hawmin III, during whose reign the Wiltun settlement grew from a fishing village into a walled city.

Value.value: This is not the head of a monster; Rogerio, recalling his Historie of Island Nomads, clearly described the ancient human tribes in the Moonshae Islands as having similar features - modern remnants of the tribe in the Moonshaes still, to this day, paint their faces in dark red clay when preparing for war. The same people who aided the Wiltun dynasty in establishing power on the island now appear the victim. Did their accord break down? Or could it be that this race of humans were enslaved by the northlanders, used to fight off the monstrous tribes of the island, forced to build the first walled cities for the budding jarldoms? If so, their rebellion led to their extinction.

Despite its monstrous appearance, the red skin and the black eyes, the head is eerily human-looking. Primordial, yes, but you have heard tell of strange tribes in the world with more brutish features akin to this. But none with such oddly-colored skin and black eyes.
You thought orcs and trolls were bad? You wouldn't want to meet this wicked-looking thing in the dead of night. And thanks to Hawmin IV, you won't have to.

value.0:
Click to investigate.

 An old oak weapon rack, its surface polished, well-maintained, and sporting the carved heraldry of the Wiltun dynasty of Ruathym's southernmost jarldom. Lord Jasht, two generations removed from Hawmin IV, lived in a time when all four jarldoms had been firmly established throughout the Ruathym island chain. Jasht was renowned for his incredible sportsmanship and success at the game of jousting, and it was through this game that he impressed and earned the hand of the Chief Axe of Ruathym's daughter by beating out all of her suitors, competing lords from the other jarldoms.

Value.value: It is no wonder how Jasht came to bring the Wiltun dynasty into so much favor during his generation; when the Chief Axe offers his daughter's hand in marriage to the best jouster, it would be foolish for any lord of a jarldom not to tip the scales in his favor - that red lance is clearly enchanted by a kind of old, theurgic magic. You notice two similar symbols beginning and ending the eldritch phrase, a variation on "force", one being force of impact, the other being reinforcement. Clearly, the lance was enchanted to knock a man out of his saddle, and enchanted against easily shattering.

Jasht had a lot to gain from succeeding at joust. The Chief Axe of Ruathym, if your history is correct, was kind of like the king of Ruathym, with all jarldoms paying fealty to him in a feudal system. To marry his daughter would bring your jarldom into great status. You recognize some engraved arcane symbols on the handle of the red lance, but they're in an unfamiliar form.

These are mighty fine lances for jousting, mighty fine. Sure, they would need to be reinforced a little after so many years to be used again, but you could still knock a guy off a horse with one without it splintering. It also looks like Jasht had his name engraved into the handle of the red lance in old, funny-looking letters.

Click to investigate.

"The twang heard 'round the island" came from this masterpiece of thirteenth century warfare, an innovation of Chief Axe Wiltun II, grandson of Lord Jasht of the Wiltun dynasty. When civil war broke out amongst the jarldoms of Ruathym, warring armies with thier foreign armies laid siege to Castle Ruathym. Chief Axe Wiltun had these highly maneuverable ballistae wheeled out of a ditch dug on the inward side of the moat and not only sank the boarding skiffs crossing the moat but levelled a significant portion of the rebelling armies. Wiltun II represents the true hey day of the Wiltun dynasty, when the family held control of the capital city through Jasht's betrothal.
Chief Axe Wiltun II's Civil War Ballista

Value.value: You recognize this as an arbalest, but must contend with the assertion that Wiltun II was its innovator. This form of the ballista war machine was in fact invented fifty years prior to the Ruathym civil war by a company of Waterdhavian dwarves who acted as war profiteers in many land skirmishes on the Faerunian mainland. Clearly Wiltun II either borrowed or purchased their technology on the sly, and with it, further cemeted the Wiltun dynasty's power.

A remarkable innovation to previously clunky ballistas, this model, known across Toril as the arbalet, would certainly have turned the tide of this war in favor of Wiltun II. When many of them are aligned, the sheer force of their projectiles and the speed and ease of their reloading can make it nigh impossible for standing armies to successfully siege a castle, especially when they have to cross a moat.
You've seen bigger ballistas. This thing is piddly. No one could win a land war nowadays with this peashooter!

value.0:
Click to investigate.

The Ruathym Civil War lasted into the generation of Chief Axe Wiltun III, son of Chief Axe Wiltun II, where it ended in the defeat of the rebelling jarldoms and the reestablishment of feudal order across the Ruathym island chain. This cold steel sword with a surpsing padded handle is imbedded in the marble pedestal; a hundred or more names are engraved in descending rings around the base of the marble pedestal, in memoriam.
The Peaceblade of Lord Wiltun III

Value.value: Judging from the padded handle, the Peaceblade brought peace only through bloodshed, the padded handle being a feature common to an executioner's weapon, to keep his hand from blistering and his aim upon the neck form during heavy executions in wartime. In fact, you recognize many of the family names on the memorial pedestal as political rivals to the Wiltun dynasty's holdings at home and abroad, particularly creditors. It must have been very convenient to the Wiltun dynasty to declare them rebels and have them drawn and quartered to avoid paying a long-standing debt for mercenaries hired and weapons commissioned during the civil war.

It is an immaculate sword, but calling it the Peaceblade may be affording too much generosity. That soft-grip handle was a common feature of executioner's blades and axes, to avoid creating welts on the hands of the executioner's who had a lot of work to do during wartime. In fact, those names on the pedestal might be victims of execution, not comrades fallen in battle.

Chief Axe Wiltun III brought peace back to Ruathym through this sword. The names engraved so austerely into the marble pedestal must be the names of trusted allies and friends who died in the civil war, so you suddenly have something else you can drink in tribute to at the local tavern. Cheers!
